description: The screenshot displays the Windows XP desktop with the "Start" button located on the taskbar. The mouse cursor hovers over the "Start" button, indicating the user is about to interact with it.  No other menus, windows, or dialog boxes are open. This suggests the next step in the manual will involve clicking the "Start" button to access system options or applications.

- New Elements: The Start Menu is now visible, displaying program shortcuts and system options. 
- Layout/Appearance Changes: The mouse cursor, previously described as hovering over the "Start" button, is no longer visible in the screenshot.

The screenshot shows the Windows XP "Start" menu open with the mouse cursor hovering over the "Control Panel" option. A yellow tooltip box explains the function of the Control Panel: "Provides options for you to customize the appearance and functionality of your computer, add or remove programs, and set up network connections and user accounts."
- The tooltip box describing the Control Panel is no longer visible.

The screenshot displays the Windows XP Control Panel in Category view. The mouse cursor hovers over the "Appearance and Themes" category, highlighting it. This category provides access to settings for changing the visual appearance of the desktop, applying themes, customizing the screen saver, and adjusting the Start menu and taskbar.
- The "Appearance and Themes" category is highlighted in blue, indicating it is being hovered over by the mouse cursor.

The screenshot displays the "Appearance and Themes" window within the Windows XP Control Panel. The mouse cursor hovers over the "Display" icon, indicating the user's next action is to click it. This will open the "Display Properties" window, allowing access to settings related to the computer's display, including screen resolution, color calibration, and screen savers.
- The mouse cursor, not mentioned in the description, is now visible and positioned over the "Display" icon.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Themes" tab. 

At the top, a tabbed interface allows navigation between "Themes," "Desktop," "Screen Saver," "Appearance," and "Settings." The currently active "Themes" tab is highlighted.  

The window showcases the currently applied theme, labeled "Windows XP (Modified)," within a dropdown menu. Below, a preview pane displays a sample image representing the chosen theme. 

Three buttons are visible at the bottom of the window:

- **OK:** This button is inactive, indicating changes made within this window have not yet been applied.
- **Cancel:** Clicking this button will close the "Display Properties" window without saving any changes made to the theme settings.
- **Apply:** This button is also inactive, as no changes to the theme settings have been made.

- Content Changes: The "Screen Saver" tab is now highlighted instead of the "Themes" tab.
- Content Changes: The preview pane now displays an image related to the "Screen Saver" settings instead of the theme preview. 
- Content Changes: The "OK" and "Apply" buttons are now active.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu shows "Windows XP" is selected, but the "Wait" time is set to "10 minutes." The checkbox "On resume, password protect" is unchecked. Below, a "Monitor power" section provides a brief instruction: "To adjust monitor power settings and save energy, click Power."  A "Power..." button is available to access these settings. 

At the bottom of the window, three buttons are visible: "OK," "Cancel," and "Apply."  Currently, none of these buttons appear to be pressed or in an active state.
- **Content Changes:** The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu now displays "None" as the selected option, instead of "Windows XP."

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu is open, showing "None" selected at the top of the list. This list contains various pre-installed screen saver options for the user to choose from. 

Below the preview window, there are three buttons:
 - **Settings:** Currently inactive (greyed out), this button would allow the user to customize the selected screen saver.
 - **Preview:** Also inactive, clicking this button would typically show a preview of the chosen screen saver.
 - **Power...:** This button opens the "Power Options Properties" window, allowing access to power management settings.

At the bottom of the window, two standard buttons are visible:
 - **Apply:**  Clicking this button would apply any changes made within the "Display Properties" window.
 - **Cancel:** This button allows the user to close the "Display Properties" window without saving any changes.

- Content Changes: 
    - The "Wait:" time has changed from an empty field to "10". 
    - The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu, described as open, is now closed.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

The "Screen saver" dropdown menu is set to "[None]", disabling the screen saver feature. Below, a numerical field labeled "Wait" is set to "10" minutes, representing the idle time before the screen saver would activate (if one was selected). The checkbox "On resume, password protect" is unchecked. 

Under the "Monitor power" section, the user is about to click the "Power" button. This button opens the "Power Options Properties" window, allowing adjustments to the monitor's power-saving settings. 

At the bottom of the window, the standard "OK", "Cancel", and "Apply" buttons are visible. These buttons respectively apply changes, discard changes, and apply changes without closing the window.

- New Elements: The "Power Options Properties" window is now visible, overlaying the "Display Properties" window. 
- Content Changes: The previously described "Display Properties" window, while still visible in the background, is no longer the primary focus. The active window title bar now reads "Power Options Properties".

The screenshot displays the "Power Options Properties" window in Windows XP. 

The "Home/Office Desk" power scheme is currently selected in the "Power schemes" dropdown menu. This menu allows users to choose from pre-set power plans or custom ones they have created. 

Below, the "Settings for Home/Office Desk power scheme" section displays four adjustable power-saving options:

* **"Turn off monitor:"**  Currently set to "After 20 mins," this dropdown menu dictates how long the computer will remain idle before the monitor switches off. 
* **"Turn off hard disks:"** Set to "Never," this dropdown menu controls the idle time before the hard drive powers down.
* **"System standby:"**  Also set to "Never," this dropdown menu manages the idle time before the computer enters standby mode.
* **"System hibernates:"**  Set to "Never," this dropdown menu determines the idle time before the computer enters hibernation. 

At the bottom of the window, three buttons offer different actions:

* **"OK:"**  Clicking this button applies any changes made within the "Power Options Properties" window and closes the window.
* **"Cancel:"**  This button closes the "Power Options Properties" window without saving any changes made during the session.
* **"Apply:"**  This button, not currently in focus, applies any changes made within the "Power Options Properties" window without closing it, allowing for further adjustments.
- The "Turn off monitor" dropdown menu is now expanded and the mouse cursor is hovering over it.

The screenshot displays the "Power Options Properties" window in Windows XP. 

The "Home/Office Desk" power scheme is currently selected in the "Power schemes" dropdown menu. This menu allows users to choose from pre-set power plans or custom ones. 

Below, four power management options are shown: "Turn off monitor," "Turn off hard disks," "System standby," and "System hibernates." Each option has a dropdown menu next to it, currently displaying "Never" for all. These menus allow users to define after what period of inactivity the system should execute the corresponding power-saving action. 

At the bottom of the window, the "Cancel" button is visible. Clicking this button will close the "Power Options Properties" window without saving any changes made to the selected power scheme.

- The "Power schemes" dropdown menu now displays "Always On" instead of "Home/Office Desk." 
- The "OK" button at the bottom of the window now appears to be highlighted, indicating it is currently active or in focus.

Under the "Power Schemes" tab, the "Home/Office Desk" power scheme is currently selected.  Four dropdown menus labeled "Turn off monitor", "Turn off hard disks", "System standby", and "System hibernates" are each set to "Never".

Additionally, the "Power Schemes", "Advanced", "Hibernate", and "UPS" tabs are visible at the top of the window, allowing the user to navigate between different power management settings.

- Content Changes:

The screenshot displays the "Power Options Properties" window in Windows XP. 

**Key Elements:**

- **"Power Schemes" Tab:** Currently active tab, indicating the focus on power management settings.
- **"Power schemes" Dropdown Menu:** Displays a list of pre-configured power schemes. The "Always On" scheme is currently selected.
- **Power Options:** A list of system power actions with corresponding dropdown menus to define their behavior. 
    - **"Turn off monitor," "Turn off hard disks," "System standby," "System hibernates":** Each option is set to "Never" in the dropdown menu. This dictates that none of these power-saving features will activate.
- **"OK" Button:** Applies the selected power scheme and settings.
- **"Cancel" Button:** Closes the "Power Options Properties" window without saving any changes.
- **"Apply" Button:** Applies the selected power scheme and settings without closing the window.

**Current State:**

The screenshot shows the user has selected the "Always On" power scheme and configured all available power options to "Never." This configuration, if applied, would disable all automatic power-saving features, keeping the monitor, hard disks, and system active indefinitely. However, the user is currently choosing to click the "Cancel" button, meaning these settings will not be applied.
- The mouse cursor, not mentioned in the initial description, is now visible and positioned over the "Cancel" button.

The screenshot displays the "Power Options Properties" window within the Windows XP Control Panel. 

The "Always On" power scheme is currently selected in the "Power schemes" dropdown menu. This scheme is designed to maximize system performance by keeping all components active. 

The "Settings for 'Always On' power scheme" section allows customization of inactivity-based power-saving features.  Each setting features a dropdown menu to adjust the timing:

* **"Turn off monitor:"**  Currently set to "After 20 mins," this option determines the delay before the monitor enters power-saving mode.
* **"Turn off hard disks:"**  Set to "Never," this option disables automatic hard drive spin-down after a period of inactivity.
* **"System standby:"** Also set to "Never," this disables automatic transition to standby mode after a period of inactivity.
* **"System hibernates:"** Set to "Never," this disables automatic hibernation after a period of inactivity.

At the bottom of the window, three buttons offer actions related to the power scheme settings:

* **"OK":**  Clicking this button applies the currently displayed settings and closes the window.
* **"Cancel":** Clicking this button closes the window without implementing any changes to the power scheme.
* **"Apply":**  This button is not visible in the screenshot. 

The mouse cursor hovers over the "Turn off hard disks" dropdown menu, indicating the user is currently focused on this specific setting.

The screenshot displays the "Appearance and Themes" window within the Windows XP Control Panel. 

On the left side, two main sections are visible:

* **"See Also":** This section provides quick access to related settings:
    * **"Fonts":** Opens the Fonts folder to manage system fonts.
    * **"Mouse Pointers":** Allows customization of the mouse pointer appearance.
    * **"High Contrast":** Provides options for high contrast display settings.
    * **"User Account Picture":**  Allows changing the user profile picture. 

* **"Troubleshooters":** This section offers help with common issues:
    * **"Display":** Launches a troubleshooter for display-related problems.
    * **"Sound":** Launches a troubleshooter for sound-related problems.

The central area of the window presents the heading "Pick a task..." followed by a list of common actions:

* **"Change the computer's theme":** Opens the Display Properties window to modify the visual theme.
* **"Change the desktop background":**  Opens the Display Properties window to change the desktop wallpaper.
* **"Choose a screen saver":** Opens the Display Properties window to select and configure a screen saver.
* **"Change the screen resolution":** Opens the Display Properties window to adjust the screen resolution settings.

Below the list of tasks, the window suggests "or pick a Control Panel icon" and displays two icons:

* **"Display":** Opens the Display Properties window for comprehensive display settings.
* **"Taskbar and Start Menu":** Opens the Taskbar and Start Menu Properties window for customization.
